### STM - Structural Topic Models
\begin{itemize}
\item STMs are another form of topic models that provide for the inclusion of covariates to help explain topic prevalence ($X^p_i$) and content ($X^c_i$).  \par \vspace{2.5mm} \pause 
\item For each document -- Model first decides how much of each topic is likely to appear (topic prevalence) – this can be driven by features like authorship, publication date, etc. \par \vspace{2.5mm} \pause 
\item For each word in document -- Model picks a topic according to those proportions and generates the word from that topic. \par \vspace{2.5mm}
\item  It’s a way to combine topic discovery with regression-style analysis, giving you richer insights into both what topics are present and how they’re talked about.
\end{itemize}


### STM Example (Setup)
\scriptsize
```{r stm_ex_setup}
texts <- apply(AssociatedPress, 1, function(x) {
  paste(rep(colnames(AssociatedPress), x), collapse = " ")
})

texts_reduced <- vapply(texts, reduce_complexity, character(1))

corpus_reduced <- VCorpus(VectorSource(texts_reduced))

dtm_reduced <- DocumentTermMatrix( corpus_reduced,
  control = list(wordLengths = c(1, Inf))
)

dfm_ap <- as.dfm(dtm_reduced)

docs_stm <- convert(dfm_ap, to = "stm") # STM Structure

meta <- data.frame(dummy = rep(1, length(docs_stm$documents))) # Document Meta

```


### STM Example
\scriptsize
```{r stm_ex}

stm_model <- stm::stm(
  documents  = docs_stm$documents,
  vocab      = docs_stm$vocab,
  K          = 5,
  prevalence = ~1,
  data       = meta,
  init.type  = "Spectral",
  seed       = 1234,
  max.em.its = 500,
  verbose    = FALSE
)

```


### STM Example (Cont.)
\scriptsize
```{r stm_ex_cont}

stm::labelTopics(stm_model, n = 10) # Top Words/Topic

proportions <- stm_model$theta # Document-Topic Proportions
round(proportions[1:10, ], 2)

```

### STM Example (Cont.)
\scriptsize
```{r stm_ex_Cont}
topic_word_probs <- exp(stm_model$beta$logbeta[[1]]) #Topic Word Probabilities
head(round(topic_word_probs[,1:5], 5))

```


